         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] if he sacrificed (for a year), striving for merit</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] (doing homage) to the sincere is better (?)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] with (the malicious) and those who rejoice in wealth [TB] with the malicious (and those who rejoice in wealth)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] (association with the evil) is bad [SKT] With the faithful (and the beautiful,)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] the wise man should make (friends)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] having heard (these eloquent words from them)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] the man (who keeps) low company (becomes low himself)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] (Arrived at the excellent) he goes to the [even] better</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] (the most excellent is attained by him who) constantly [TB] the most excellent (is attained by him who constantly)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] in virtue and in calmness</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels"><ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht307"/>-<ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht308"/>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:bernhard1965"/><citedRange>309-311</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:hahn2007"/><citedRange>86-87</citedRange></bibl></note><note type="remarks">On <ref target="http://idp.bl.uk/database/oo_loader.a4d?pm=IOL%20Toch%20884" type="external">IDP</ref>, the images are upside down.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">Uv.24.30b <hi>saṃvatsaraṃ yajati puṇyaprekṣī</hi></note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">This is a difficult line, because the Sanskrit text is lacking. <hi>lki</hi>, which can be read if the piece flipped over to the verso is considered, must be from <hi>telki</hi> and combined with <hi>yam-</hi> it must mean ‘honour’ or ‘sacrifice’ (the equation <hi>telki</hi> ~ <hi>yajña</hi> is attested in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht541"/> a4). <bibl><title corresp="ref:bernhard1965"/></bibl>’s reconstruction <hi>puṇyaprekṣī</hi> is confirmed by <hi>yarpo lk· ///</hi>, which must contain a form of <hi>ləka-</hi> ‘see’, but his <hi>yajati</hi> may have to be turned into <hi>yajeta</hi> in view of the opt. in Tocharian B <hi>yāmi</hi> (and cf. Dhp.108b <hi>yajetha</hi>).</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">Uv.24.30d <hi>abhivādanaṃ tv ṛjjugateṣu śreyaḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">After <hi>(ke)k(a)moṣ</hi>, the word <hi>saim</hi> can be read, but the lower part of the ligature <hi>mXā</hi> is unclear. I would expect a form of <hi>yam-</hi> ‘to do’ and the following akṣara could either be <hi>mi</hi> or <hi>mo</hi>, both giving good possibilities (i.e. either <hi>yāmo°</hi> or <hi>yāmi</hi>), but it looks more like <hi>m[n]ā</hi>, so that I would like to leave this question open.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">Uv.25.1b <hi>piśunair vibhūtinandibhiḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">I expect <hi>wṣetstse</hi> or the like as a translation of <hi>piśuna</hi>, but there are no rests below the <hi>t</hi>. Maybe it is just very badly abraded.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">Uv.25.2a <hi>śrāddhebhiḥ peśalebhiś ca</hi></note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">Uv.25.2c <hi>sākhyaṃ kurvīta saprajñaḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Uv.25.4c <hi>teṣāṃ hi śrutvā tu subhāṣitāni</hi></note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">Uv.25.5a <hi>hīyati puruṣo nihīnasevī</hi></note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">Uv.25.5c <hi>śreṣṭham upagato hy upaiti śraiṣṭhyaṃ</hi>. We clearly read <hi>śre</hi>, so probably <hi>śre(ṣṭham)</hi>, against Bernhard’s reconstruction <hi>śraiṣṭhyaṃ</hi> Uv. 25.5c, just like <hi>(śr)e(ṣṭham)</hi> in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht308"/> a8.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">Uv.25.6a <hi>śreyo hi labhate nityaṃ</hi></note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">Uv.25.6d <hi>śīlenopaśamena ca</hi></note></p>
         </div>
